
-# Same rationale as a swiss-knife - but just bigger. 
  The saumrai sword has the following elements (in order) : 
    1. (Row 1) : 3 checkboxes 
    2. (Row 2) : 2 <select>
    3. (Row 3) : 2 push-buttons
  
  Unlike the swiss-knife - where there was one of anything - it is 
  not possible to set attributes like 'name' at render time. Any and 
  all customization has to be done, therefore, in JS. This element
  makes no assumptions about the context its being used in

  One more thing : the samurai-sword is rendered as a jQuery accordion.
  So, you sheath and un-sheath a samurai-sword

- marker = marker.blank? ? 'tbd' : marker
- label = label.blank? ? 'tbd' : label

.toolbox.samurai-sword.full-width{ :marker => "#{marker}" }
  .label.accordion-heading
  .accordion-content
    .checkbox-row
      .checkbox
        %label
        %input.left{ :type => :checkbox, :marker => "#{marker}", :disabled => true }
      .checkbox
        %label
        %input.left{ :type => :checkbox, :marker => "#{marker}", :disabled => true }
      .checkbox
        %label
        %input.left{ :type => :checkbox, :marker => "#{marker}", :disabled => true }
    .select-row
      .select
        %label
        %select.left{ :disabled => true }
      .select
        %label
        %select.left{ :disabled => true }
    .button-row
      %input.button.left{ :type => :button, :disabled => true }
      %input.button.left{ :type => :button, :disabled => true }
